.TH "NETFYR.YAML" 5 "" "" "File Formats Manual"
.SH NAME
netfyr.yaml \- netfyr policy file formats
.SH DESCRIPTION
netfyr reads YAML files from
.I /etc/netfyr/policies/
to configure network interfaces.
This page documents all supported YAML formats and their fields.
.PP
Files may contain multiple YAML documents separated by
.BR \-\-\- .
Each document is parsed independently and produces one policy.
.PP
For worked configuration examples, see
.BR netfyr\-examples (7).
.SH "BARE STATE FORMAT"
The simplest format.
A YAML document with no
.B kind
field declares the desired state of a single network entity.
It is automatically wrapped into a static policy with default priority 100
and a name derived from the filename.
.PP
The
.B selector:
sub-mapping identifies the target entity using selector properties
(see
.BR SELECTORS ).
All other top-level keys (except
.B kind
and
.BR selector )
are configuration fields that declare the desired state (see
.BR FIELDS ).
.PP
Fields:
.TP
.B selector
(mapping, required)
Identifies the target entity.
Contains selector properties:
.BR type ,
.BR name ,
.BR driver ,
.BR mac ,
.BR pci_path .
See
.B SELECTORS
below.
.TP
.B "Configuration properties (at top level)"
See
.B FIELDS
below.
For ethernet:
.BR mtu ,
.BR enabled ,
.BR ipv4 ,
.BR ipv6 .
.PP
Example:
.RS 4
.nf
selector:
  name: eth0
mtu: 1500
ipv4:
  addresses:
    \- 10.0.1.50/24
.fi
.RE
.SH "POLICY FORMAT"
A YAML document with
.BR "kind: policy" .
Provides explicit control over the factory type, priority, and naming.
.PP
Fields:
.TP
.B kind
(string, required)
Must be
.BR policy .
.TP
.B name
(string, required)
Unique policy name.
Used in conflict reports and provenance tracking.
.TP
.B factory
(string, required)
Factory type.
One of:
.BR static ,
.BR dhcpv4 ,
.BR ipv6auto .
.RS
.TP
.B static
Produces states from the literal
.B state
or
.B states
fields defined in this policy.
.TP
.B dhcpv4
Acquires an address via DHCPv4 for the interface identified by
.BR selector .
Requires the netfyr daemon to be running.
.TP
.B ipv6auto
Enables full IPv6 autoconfiguration for the interface identified by
.BR selector .
Always runs SLAAC (processing Router Advertisements for prefixes, DNS,
and routes), and conditionally starts DHCPv6 based on the M/O flags in
RAs.
The router decides whether DHCPv6 is needed, not the user.
Requires the netfyr daemon to be running.
.RE
.TP
.B priority
(integer, optional, default: 100)
Numeric priority for field-level conflict resolution.
Higher values take precedence when two policies set the same field on the
same interface.
.TP
.B selector
(mapping, required)
Identifies the target entity.
Contains selector properties (see
.BR SELECTORS ).
.TP
.B state
(mapping, optional)
Configuration fields for the target entity (e.g.,
.BR mtu ,
.BR ipv4 ,
.BR ipv6 ).
Does not contain selector fields.
Mutually exclusive with
.BR states .
Used with
.BR "factory: static" .
.TP
.B states
(sequence, optional)
A list of configuration-field mappings.
Each entry contains only configuration fields.
Used when a policy produces multiple entities.
Mutually exclusive with
.BR state .
Used with
.BR "factory: static" .
.PP
Example (static, single state):
.RS 4
.nf
kind: policy
name: server\-network
factory: static
priority: 150
selector:
  name: eth0
state:
  mtu: 9000
  ipv4:
    addresses:
      \- 10.0.1.50/24
  ipv6:
    addresses:
      \- 2001:db8::50/64
.fi
.RE
.PP
Example (static, multiple states):
.RS 4
.nf
kind: policy
name: server\-network
factory: static
priority: 150
selector:
  name: eth0
states:
  \- mtu: 9000
    ipv4:
      addresses:
        \- 10.0.1.50/24
.fi
.RE
.PP
Example (dhcpv4):
.RS 4
.nf
kind: policy
name: eth0\-dhcp
factory: dhcpv4
selector:
  name: eth0
.fi
.RE
.PP
Example (ipv6auto):
.RS 4
.nf
kind: policy
name: eth0\-ipv6
factory: ipv6auto
selector:
  name: eth0
.fi
.RE
.SH "MULTI-DOCUMENT FILES"
A single YAML file may contain multiple documents separated by
.BR \-\-\- .
Each document is parsed independently and produces one policy.
.PP
Example:
.RS 4
.nf
selector:
  name: eth0
mtu: 9000
\-\-\-
selector:
  name: eth1
mtu: 1500
.fi
.RE
.SH SELECTORS
Selector fields identify which system entity a state targets.
They are always written inside a
.B selector:
mapping \(em either at the top level of a bare state document or at the
policy level of an explicit policy document.
All specified selector fields must match (AND logic).
.TP
.B type
(string, optional)
Entity type filter (e.g.,
.BR ethernet ).
Used for technology filtering when the selector would otherwise match
multiple entity types.
.TP
.B name
(string)
Exact interface name (e.g.,
.BR eth0 ).
.TP
.B driver
(string)
Kernel driver name (e.g.,
.BR ixgbe ).
.TP
.B pci_path
(string)
PCI device path (e.g.,
.BR 0000:03:00.0 ).
.TP
.B mac
(string)
MAC address in colon-separated hexadecimal (e.g.,
.BR aa:bb:cc:dd:ee:ff ).
Comparison is case-insensitive.
.SH FIELDS
Configuration fields are written at the top level of a bare state document
(outside the
.B selector:
mapping) or inside the
.B state:
mapping of an explicit policy.
The available fields depend on the entity type.
.SS "Ethernet fields (top level)"
The following fields apply to
.BR "type: ethernet"
at the top level of the state.
.TP
.B mtu
(integer)
Maximum transmission unit in bytes.
Valid range: 68\(en65535.
.TP
.B enabled
(boolean)
Administrative state of the interface.
.B true
brings the interface up;
.B false
brings it down.
.SS "Ethernet fields (ipv4 sub-object)"
.TP
.B ipv4
(mapping, optional, keep-when-absent)
IPv4 configuration sub-object.
Omitting
.B ipv4
entirely means \(lqdon\(aqt touch IPv4 config\(rq.
An explicit empty mapping
.RB ( "ipv4: {}" )
means \(lqmanage IPv4, remove unspecified\(rq.
.TP
.B ipv4.addresses
(sequence of strings)
IPv4 addresses assigned to the interface, in CIDR notation
(e.g.,
.BR 10.0.1.50/24 ).
Order is preserved: the first address becomes the primary (source) address.
Duplicate addresses are rejected.
.TP
.B ipv4.routes
(sequence of mappings)
Static IPv4 routes to configure.
Each route mapping supports the following keys:
.RS
.TP
.B destination
(string, required)
Route destination in CIDR notation (e.g.,
.BR 0.0.0.0/0 ).
.TP
.B gateway
(string, optional)
Next-hop IPv4 address (e.g.,
.BR 10.0.1.1 ).
.TP
.B metric
(integer, optional)
Route metric (lower values are preferred).
.TP
.B mtu
(integer, optional)
Route MTU in bytes.
.TP
.B table
(integer, optional)
Routing table ID.
Default is 254 (main table).
.TP
.B tos
(integer, optional)
Type of Service (TOS/DSCP) filter.
Valid range: 0\(en255.
.TP
.B protocol
(string, optional)
Route protocol (e.g.,
.BR static ,
.BR dhcp ,
.BR kernel ).
.RE
.SS "Ethernet fields (ipv6 sub-object)"
.TP
.B ipv6
(mapping, optional, keep-when-absent)
IPv6 configuration sub-object.
Omitting
.B ipv6
entirely means \(lqdon\(aqt touch IPv6 config\(rq.
An explicit empty mapping
.RB ( "ipv6: {}" )
means \(lqmanage IPv6, remove unspecified\(rq.
.TP
.B ipv6.addresses
(sequence of strings or mappings)
IPv6 addresses assigned to the interface, in CIDR notation
(e.g.,
.BR 2001:db8::1/64 ).
Each item may be a plain string or a mapping with lifetime attributes:
.RS
.TP
.B address
(string, required)
The IPv6 address in CIDR notation.
.TP
.B valid_lft
(integer, optional)
Valid lifetime in seconds.
.TP
.B preferred_lft
(integer, optional)
Preferred lifetime in seconds.
.RE
.TP
.B ipv6.routes
(sequence of mappings)
Static IPv6 routes to configure.
Each route mapping supports the following keys:
.RS
.TP
.B destination
(string, required)
Route destination in IPv6 CIDR notation (e.g.,
.BR ::/0 ).
.TP
.B gateway
(string, optional)
Next-hop IPv6 address (e.g.,
.BR fe80::1 ).
.TP
.B metric
(integer, optional)
Route metric (lower values are preferred).
.RE
.TP
.B ipv6.link_local
(string, optional, keep-when-absent)
Link-local address generation mode.
Accepted values:
.B eui64
(default) or
.BR none .
Controls the kernel\(aqs
.B addr_gen_mode
sysctl.
Must be set before the interface is brought up.
.TP
.B ipv6.dad_transmits
(integer, optional, keep-when-absent)
Number of DAD (Duplicate Address Detection) probes to send.
0 disables DAD.
Default: kernel default (usually 1).
.SH "VALUE TYPES"
YAML scalars are mapped to netfyr internal types as follows:
.TP
.B "YAML boolean"
netfyr
.B Bool
.TP
.B "YAML integer >= 0"
netfyr
.B U64
.TP
.B "YAML integer < 0"
netfyr
.B I64
.TP
.B "YAML string (valid IPv4 or IPv6 address)"
netfyr
.B IpAddr
(e.g.,
.B 10.0.0.1
or
.BR ::1 ).
Both IPv4 and IPv6 addresses are supported.
.TP
.B "YAML string (valid CIDR prefix)"
netfyr
.B IpNetwork
(e.g.,
.B 10.0.0.0/24
or
.BR ::/0 ).
Both IPv4 and IPv6 prefixes are supported.
The deserializer tries IpNetwork first (CIDR with prefix length),
then IpAddr (bare address), then falls back to String.
.TP
.B "YAML string (other)"
netfyr
.B String
.TP
.B "YAML sequence"
netfyr
.B List
.TP
.B "YAML mapping"
netfyr
.B Map
.SH FILES
.TP
.I /etc/netfyr/policies/
Policy and bare state YAML files.
Loaded at daemon startup and when
.B netfyr apply
is invoked.
.TP
.I /var/lib/netfyr/policies/
Daemon-persisted policies managed automatically by the netfyr daemon.
Do not edit these files by hand.
